node.text:
💧 With Hubble data, astronomers found evidence of water vapor in the atmosphere of Jupiter’s moon Ganymede!

This is an ice-covered world that might hold more water than all of Earth’s oceans combined… but Ganymede’s oceans exist below a 100-mile-thick, icy crust.

This atmospheric water vapor was formed in a process called sublimation, when a solid turns directly into a gas (ice ➡️ water vapor).

Find out more about this discovery at the link in our bio!

#NASA #Hubble #video #Jupiter #Ganymede #moon #planet #space #solarsystem #water #news

node.title: Hubble Finds Evidence of Water Vapor at Jupiter’s Moon Ganymede

Their efforts helped ensure that Hubble’s exploration of the universe is far from over. Read more at the link in our bio!

Dark matter is the “invisible glue” that holds the universe together.

All galaxies seem to be dominated by it, but Hubble observations of an oddball galaxy lacking dark matter are challenging theories of galaxy formation.

Learn more about this cosmic mystery at the link in our bio!

🔵 Dual nature 🔴

These #HubbleFriday views of the star AG Carinae show the final acts of this huge star’s life.

The first image’s blue hues show the distribution of dust that shines in reflected star light. The second image shows details of ionized hydrogen and nitrogen emissions from the expanding gas shell around the star.

This nebula surrounding AG Carinae is about five light-years wide, which is similar to the distance from here to the nearest star beyond our Sun – Proxima Centauri.

Learn more and try out our interactive image slider at the link in our bio!

Take a listen to Westerlund 2 👂

This spectacular cluster is full of young stars, about one to two million years old. Westerlund 2 is roughly 20,000 light-years away from us!

Through sonification, we can interpret information from this beautiful image in a whole new way... data from Hubble and @nasachandraxray is represented in sound!

Brighter light is assigned louder sound, and the pitch of the notes indicates the vertical position of the sources in the image with the higher pitches towards the top of the image.

The Hubble data is played by strings and Chandra's X-ray data is represented by bells.

node.text:
Got any plans for 2037?

A supernova “replay” is expected to appear in about 16 years, thanks to the gravity from an enormous galaxy cluster that lies between us and the faraway supernova. The gravity magnified and distorted the light from the supernova blast, splitting it into multiple copies.

Three mirror images of Supernova Requiem were spotted by Hubble scattered in an arc-like pattern across the cluster. Each image shows the supernova’s light at different times after the explosive event, and a fourth copy is likely to show up in 2037.

The prediction of the supernova's return appearance is based on computer models of the cluster, which describe the various paths the supernova light is taking through the maze of clumpy dark matter in the galaxy cluster. Dark matter is an invisible material that makes up most of the universe's matter and is the scaffolding upon which galaxies and galaxy clusters are built.

You can think about the supernova’s different light paths like this: Several trains leave a station at the same time, all traveling at the same speed and bound for the same location. Each train, however, takes a different route, and the distance for each route is not the same. Because the trains travel over different track lengths across different terrain, they do not arrive at their destination at the same time.

Find out more at the link in our bio!

Credits: Steve A. Rodney (University of South Carolina), Gabriel Brammer (Cosmic Dawn Center/Niels Bohr Institute/University of Copenhagen); Image Processing: Joseph DePasquale (STScI)

What’s your sign? If you’re a Sagittarius, you’re in luck. ♐

Today’s #HubbleFriday shows a beautiful star cluster located in the constellation Sagittarius. Called NGC 6717, this is a globular cluster – which is a roughly spherical grouping of stars that are tightly bound together by gravity.

This cluster is over 20,000 light-years away, but some of the stars in this image are a little closer to home.

At the center of the image, the stars with crisscross spikes are actually bright foreground stars that lie between Earth and this cluster.

Let’s take a trip around a gas giant 🚀

Jupiter’s trademark is its "Great Red Spot" which is the oval roughly the width of Earth. With a deep atmosphere containing hydrogen and helium, and jet streams blowing in opposite directions and different latitudes, Jupiter is a unique planetary destination in our solar system. 

Thanks to Hubble’s Wide Field Camera 3, scientists are able to produce maps of Jupiter using data gathered during Hubble Outer Planet Atmospheres Legacy program observations, which can then be projected onto a rotating globe. This program provides yearly global views of outer planets to help track changes in storms, winds, and cloud patterns. 

Credit: NASA, ESA, A. Simon (GSFC), M. Wong (UC Berkeley), G. Orton (JPL-Caltech), and G. Bacon (STScI)

Hubble “boldly goes” where no telescope has gone before.

For #StarTrekDay, here’s a (final) Frontier Field image of the galaxy cluster AbellS1063, located four billion light-years away. The Frontier Fields program sought to probe the early universe by studying large galaxy clusters like this one.

Thanks to Hubble's powerful vision, this picture unveils the effect of space warping due to gravity.

The huge mass of the galaxy cluster distorts and magnifies the light from galaxies that lie far behind it due to an effect called gravitational lensing, which allows Hubble to see galaxies that would otherwise be too small and faint to observe.

This "warp field" makes it possible to get a peek at the very first generation of galaxies!

Image credits: NASA, ESA,and J. Lotz (STScI)

Let’s take a look 30 million light-years away 👀

Here's a #HubbleClassic view showing the galaxy NGC 1512’s unique core. This 2,400 light-year-wide circle of infant star clusters is called a "circumnuclear" starburst ring.

Starbursts are episodes of intense star formation.

Image credits: NASA, ESA, and D. Maoz (Tel-Aviv University and Columbia University)

node.text:
Could dying stars hold the secret to looking younger? 🤔

New evidence from Hubble suggests that white dwarf stars could continue to burn hydrogen in the final stages of their lives, causing them to appear more youthful than they actually are!

This discovery is big news, as it could change how astronomers measure the ages of star clusters, which contain the oldest known stars in the universe.

Read more at the link in our bio!

Image credits: ESA, NASA, Giampaolo Piotto

May the #HubbleFriday force be with you! 🤩

This cosmic view isn’t a lightsaber, though. It's a Herbig-Haro object, formed when a young star ejects jets of material into space!

These hot jets collide with clouds of gas and dust surrounding newly formed stars at speeds of hundreds of miles per second to create Herbig-Haro objects such as HH111, pictured here.

For more information, visit the link in our bio!

Image credits: ESA/Hubble & NASA, B. Nisini

A magnetic force to be reckoned with 🧲✨

This stunning galaxy called NGC 1275 contains red filaments near its center which are shaped by a strong magnetic field. These lacy structures are fine threads of gas up to 20,000 light-years long and 200 light-years wide.

Observing these filaments allows astronomers to estimate the strength of the magnetic field and how these filaments maintain their structure despite gravitational forces.

Credit: NASA, ESA, M. Kornmesser and L. Christensen (ESA/Hubble), and G. Bacon (STScI); Science: NASA, ESA, and the Hubble Heritage (STScI/AURA)-ESA/Hubble Collaboration
